09.Example 2

Modified

Fr 2024-09-06 06:54

Given:

Experiments have been conducted on a metallic cylinder \(12.7\ \mathrm{mm}\) in diameter and \(94\ \mathrm{mm}\) long. The cylinder is heated internally by an electrical heater and is subjected to a cross flow of air in a low-speed wind tunnel. Under a specific set of operating conditions for which the upstream air velocity and temperature were maintained at \(V = 10\ \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}\) and \(26.2\ \mathrm{Â°C}\), respectively, the heater power dissipation was measured to be \(P = 46\ \mathrm{W}\), while the average cylinder surface temperature was determined to be \(T_s = 128.4\ \mathrm{Â°C}\). It is estimated that \(15.0\%\) of the power dissipation is lost through the cumulative effect of surface radiation and conduction through the end pieces.

Required:

  1. Determine the convection heat transfer coefficient from the experimental observations.
  2. Compare the experimental result with the convection coefficient computed from an appropriate correlation.

Solution:

Start first by defining all of the given values.

\[D = 12.7\ \mathrm{mm}\] \[L = 94\ \mathrm{mm}\] \[V = 10\ \frac{\mathrm{m}}{\mathrm{s}}\] \[T_\infty = 26.2\ \mathrm{Â°C} = 299.35\ \mathrm{K}\] \[P = 46\ \mathrm{W}\] \[T_s = 128.4\ \mathrm{Â°C} = 401.55\ \mathrm{K}\] \[f_l = 15.0\%\]

A drawing of the actual component being analyzed is shown below.

The heat rate as given by experimental observations is

\[ q=\bar{h}A_s\left( T_s - T_\infty \right) \]

Solving for the average convective coefficient shows

\[ \bar{h}=\frac{q}{A_s \left( T_s - T_\infty \right)} \]

Reviewing the expression shows that the heat rate \(q\) and the surface area \(A_s\) must be known. The heat rate is found by the power output. Taking into account the loss through radiation and the ends of the cylinder, the heat rate is

\[ q = (1-f_l) P = 39.1\ \mathrm{W} \]

The surface area is given by

\[ A_s = \pi D L = 37.5\ \mathrm{cm}^{2} \]

The average convective coefficient is then found by

Answer (a): \(\bar{h}_1 = \frac{q}{A_s (T_s - T_\infty)} = 102.0\ \frac{\mathrm{W}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}\)

The film temperature is given by

\[ T_f = \frac{T_s+T_\infty}{2} = 350.4\ \mathrm{K} = 77.3\ \mathrm{Â°C} \]

Going to Table A.4 @ \(T_f\) shows that interpolation is needed. This is shown below.

\[T_A = 350\ \mathrm{K} = 76.9\ \mathrm{Â°C}\] \[T_B = 400\ \mathrm{K} = 126.9\ \mathrm{Â°C}\] \[\nu_A = 2.092\times 10^{-5}\ \frac{\mathrm{m}^{2}}{\mathrm{s}}\] \[\nu_B = 2.641\times 10^{-5}\ \frac{\mathrm{m}^{2}}{\mathrm{s}}\] \[ \nu = \frac{T_f - T_A}{T_B - T_A}(\nu_B - \nu_A) + \nu_A = 2.097\times 10^{-5}\ \frac{\mathrm{m}^{2}}{\mathrm{s}} \] \[k_A = 0.03\ \frac{\mathrm{W}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}\right)}\] \[k_B = 0.0338\ \frac{\mathrm{W}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}\right)}\] \[ k = \frac{T_f - T_A}{T_B - T_A}(k_B - k_A) + k_A = 30.03\ \frac{\mathrm{mW}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}\right)} \] \[Pr_A = 0.7\] \[Pr_B = 0.69\] \[ Pr = \frac{T_f - T_A}{T_B - T_A}(Pr_B - Pr_A) + Pr_A = 0.6999 \]

The Reynolds number for flow around a cylinder is defined as

\[ Re_D = \frac{V D}{\nu} = 6056.4 \]

Referring to Table 9.1 from the lecture notes, the following empirical relation is valid

\[ \bar{Nu}_D = C Re_D^{m} Pr^{\frac{1}{3}} = 37.27 \]

where \(C = 0.193\) and \(m = 0.618\).

Using the definition of the Nusselt number, the average convective coefficient may be found. This is shown below.

\[ \bar{Nu}_D=\frac{\bar{h} D}{k} \]

Solving for \(\bar{h}\) shows

Answer (b): \(\bar{h}_2 = \frac{\bar{Nu_D} k}{D} = 88.13\ \frac{\mathrm{W}}{\left(\mathrm{K} \cdot \mathrm{m}^{2}\right)}\)

The percent difference between the two methods is given by

\[ \% Diff = \Biggr\lvert \frac{\bar{h}_2 - \bar{h}_1}{\frac{\bar{h}_2+ \bar{h}_1}{2}} \Biggr\rvert = 14.6 \% \]
